🌟 Career Wisdom from "The Tao of Warren Buffett" 🌟

🚂 "Managing your career is like investing—the degree of difficulty does not count. So you can save yourself money and pain by getting on the right train."

This nugget of wisdom from No. 28 of The Tao of Warren Buffett by Mary Buffett and David Clark speaks for itself:

"One not only needs to learn what kind of business to invest in but what kind to work in. If one goes to work for a company with poor long-term economics, then he can never expect to do really well because the company doesn’t do well. Salaries will be below average and raises will be few and long between, and there is greater risk of losing your job because management will always be under pressure to cut costs."

💡 Key Takeaway: Choose companies with strong long-term economics and high margins. You'll find higher salaries, more frequent raises, and ample room for promotions. After all, working at a successful company is like hopping onto a first-class train ride to Easy Street! 🚂✨

🛑 Avoid Companies with low margins and poor economics. They lead to a "long, slow, hard freight-train ride to a Siberian nowhere." 🚧❄️
Read more about Warren Buffett’s career advice in The Tao of Warren Buffett. The page speaks for itself! 📖

🚀 Exciting News: Our Research Paper on Blockchain-Based Academic Bank of Credit Management System for Higher Education: An Innovative Approach to Student Credentialing and Progression is Published in IEEE Conference! 📚🔗
I am thrilled to share that our research paper on the groundbreaking use of blockchain in education has been successfully published in the IEEE conference! 🎉
In this research, I explored the immense potential of blockchain technology in reshaping the education landscape. Imagine a future where courses, certifications, and student information are securely stored on an immutable blockchain, ushering in a new era of transparency and trust in academics.
One of the most exciting aspects of our research is the integration of degree certifications into the blockchain. This not only eliminates the risk of counterfeit certificates but also provides a verifiable and tamper-proof record of a student's academic achievements. The blockchain becomes a digital vault for degrees, enhancing the credibility of educational qualifications.
I want to express my sincere gratitude to the IEEE ICBDS 2023 conference for providing a platform to share and discuss these innovative ideas. Additionally, I extend my thanks to Dr. Amar Buchade for successfully conducting the conference, collaborators Aishwarya Shukla, Dr. Manisha Mali, Prajwal Waykos and the academic community for their valuable insights and support throughout this journey.

It's straightforward prompt-building:

• Tell the agent what it aims to do
• Give it tools
• Show examples
• Give it a task

The agent uses chain-of-thought reasoning to identify its task and outputs Python code using the tools. It comes with a myriad of built-in tools such as document, text, image QA, Speech-to-text and text-to-speech, text classification, summarization, translation, image edition tools, text-to-video...

The use of AI anchors in news reporting has both advantages and disadvantages. One advantage is that they can deliver news reports with a consistent tone and delivery, without the need for breaks or rest. Additionally, they can work 24/7, providing news reports at any time of the day or night.

However, one disadvantage is that AI anchors lack human emotions and may not be able to convey the same level of empathy or connection with viewers that human anchors can. This lack of emotional connection may result in a loss of trust or credibility with the audience.

Furthermore, the current technology for AI anchors is still in its early stages, and there may be limitations in terms of their ability to handle breaking news or complex stories. There is also the question of whether AI anchors will be able to replace human anchors completely or if they will serve as supplements to human anchors.

Overall, the use of AI anchors in news reporting is a relatively new development, and it remains to be seen how it will evolve and be received by the audience.

Hundreds of laptops are left unused in corporate offices every year, either because they can’t run heavy office software anymore or because they are so old that they can’t be handed out to employees.

But these same laptops can be extremely useful for underprivileged students, whose families can’t afford to buy one to support their education.

I believe that access to technology can strongly boost the growth of students. If they are able to attend online classes, complete assignments, and consume more knowledgeable content, there is nothing that can stop them from building a bright future for themselves.

Over the last couple of months, through my connections in various offices in Bengaluru, I was able to collect a few laptops, get them checked for usability, and pass them over to 40 families in need.

I intend on further scaling my efforts to help more students.

Will be happy to receive leads on laptops that are sitting idle and can be reused instead of getting discarded completely.

EDIT: Thanks to the overwhelming response and the helpful suggestions shared in the comments below, I have created two Google forms to coordinate this better. text: #helloconnections A serious incedent happened in my life a couple of days ago and hence wanted to share it with you all...... The story starts about a week ago when my laptop started giving me trouble with an extremely noisy fan and intense heating..... I figured out the causes of this problem by watching some YouTube videos and the best solution I got... was to just open my laptop and put some coolent over my fan and other parts inside it...... since I was inexperienced at opening laptop(despite being a tech engineer) ... I Took it to a repairing shop nearby.....After describing my problem.... the guy said it would cost me ₹1000 for the repair.... when i  said you just have to put some coolent on it... and ₹1000 is too much for that.... the guy replied... "I have spent ₹2,00,000...to learn how to open it and do...."..... This thing hit me harder than ever.... well..... I have spent ₹20,00,000 to complete my engineering..i know exactly how a processor works...what a mother board does...which register fetches a data point from where and put it where....and still am unable to open it at all......This is something that i think we are lagging in our career..... The mechanical engineer who has a PHD.... in mechanics.... has to take his car to remove dust from his carborator where a 10th fail mechanic..... does it in no time.... Isn't it something to be ashamed of....when you call yourself an engineer.?? I sincerely hope our Education system would look upto this and try adding more practical implementations than.... pure theory which practically is available on internet..... # #education #data #career #share #tech #share #engineer #phd #engineering .. Parikshit Mahalle Prachi Joshi
